      "question": "If the sum of the first $n$ terms of an arithmetic progression is given by $S_n = 3n^2 + n$, find the $k^{th}$ term of this progression. Also, determine the common difference of the sequence.",
      "answer": "$a_k = 6k - 2$; $d = 6$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the relation $a_n = S_n - S_{n-1}$ for $n > 1$ to find the general term.",
          "Calculate $S_{k-1}$ by substituting $(k-1)$ for $n$ in the expression for $S_n$.",
          "Subtract $S_{k-1}$ from $S_k$ to obtain the $k^{th}$ term $a_k$.",
          "Find the common difference $d$ by calculating $a_k - a_{k-1}$ or $a_2 - a_1$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$S_k = 3k^2 + k \\\\ S_{k-1} = 3(k-1)^2 + (k-1) = 3(k^2 - 2k + 1) + k - 1 = 3k^2 - 6k + 3 + k - 1 = 3k^2 - 5k + 2 \\\\ a_k = S_k - S_{k-1} = (3k^2 + k) - (3k^2 - 5k + 2) \\\\ a_k = 3k^2 + k - 3k^2 + 5k - 2 = 6k - 2 \\\\ d = a_k - a_{k-1} = (6k - 2) - (6(k-1) - 2) = 6k - 2 - (6k - 6 - 2) = 6k - 2 - 6k + 8 = 6$"
      },
